ACE 1-1
• Another middle school conducted the same type of fundraiser as the middle school in the problems. The banner shows the goals for each grade.
a. Write three statements that the principal could make when comparing the goals each grade has set.

Answers may vary. Possible statements:

  • The sixth graders plan to raise $60 more than the fifth graders.
  • The fifth graders plan to raise half the amount that the seventh graders want to raise.
  • The eighth graders plan to raise the most money.
  • For every 1 dollar the fifth graders raise, the seventh graders plan to raise 2 dollars.
b. The teachers set a goal of $225. Write two statements that the principal could use to compare this goal to the eighth graders' goal.

Answers may vary. Possible statements:

  • The teachers want to raise $75 less than the eighth graders.
  • The teachers' goal is 3/4 of the eighth graders' goal.
  • For every $45 the teachers raise, the eighth graders will riase $60.

a. Consider this statement:

For every 2 pens, there are 4 pencils.

Do you agree with this statement? Explain.

Yes, I agree with this statement. Students may multiply the 2 by 6 and the 4 by 6 to get 12 pens and 24 pencils. Others mat start with "For every 2 pens, there are 4 pencils." We can show this is equivalent to "12 pens and 24 pencils" by finding the multiples of 2 pens and 4 pencils. This can be observed in the following table:
b. Write two or more statements comparing the number of pens in the class to the number of pencils.

Answers may vary. Possible statements:

  • There are twice the number of pencils as the number of pens in the classroom container.
  • There are 12 less pens than pencils in the classroom container.

ACE 1-3
The members of the Central Middle School French Club make 30 fruit skewers. They use green grapes, blueberries, and purple grapes. They make the following claims.

Claim 1

For every 90 green grapes on the skewers, they need 60 purple grapes.

Claim 2

The club likes green grapes better than blueberries.

Claim 3

For every 1 blueberry, there is 1 purple grape.

Claim 4

The ratio of purple to green grapes is 3 to 2.

Claim 5

There are more green grapes than purple grapes.

Claim 6

There are 2 blueberries for every 5 grapes.
a. Which of the claims are true?
Claims 1, 3, 5, and 6
b. Which of the claims are ratios?

Claims 1, 3, and 6. Claim 4 is an incorrect ratio.

Discussion points:

Claim 1 True Ratio

Claim 2 Can't determine—not ratio

Claim 3 True Ratio

Claim 4 False—Incorrect Ratio

Claim 5 True—not ratio

Claim 6 True Ratio

ACE 1-5
Eduardo, Karim, and Shawn are training for the school cross- country team. One day, they report the distances they ran as a comparison statements.
a. Eduardo says he ran twice as far as Karim. Give three possibilities for the distances each could have run.

Answers may vary. Possible distances:

  • Eduardo: 3 km, Karim: 1.5 km
  • Eduardo: 10 km, Karim: 5 km
  • Eduardo: 4 km, Karim: 2 km
b. Karim says that the ratio of the distance he ran to the distance Shawn ran is 4:3. Give three possibilities for the distances each could have run.

Answers may vary, Possible distances.

  • Karim: 4 km, Shawn: 3 km
  • Karim: 6 km, Shawn: 4.5 km
  • Karim: 12 km, Shawn: 9 km
c. Which runner ran the farthest? Explain.
Eduardo ran the furthest. If he ran twice as far as Karim and Karim ran further than Shawn (that is what is implied by the ratio 4:3), then Eduardo ran farther than both Karim and Shawn.
ACE 1-6
Fahari saw a fish tank that had 9 blue fish and 15 orange fish. Find the ratio that incorrectly describes the fish tank, and explain why it is incorrect.

a. For every 24 fish, 9 were blue.

b. The ratio of orange to blue fish is 9 to 15.

c. For every 3 blue fish, there were 5 orange fish.

d. The ratio of blue fish to the total is 9 to 24.
b is false; the ratio of orange to blue fish is 15 to 9
ACE 1-7

Desmond put candles on his brother's birthday cake. He used 5 blue candles, 5 green candles, and 4 red candles. Mark each ratio as true (accurate) or false (not accurate). If not accurate, try to revise to make it true. Which ratios are part to part and which are part to whole?
a. The ratio of blue to green is 1 to 1.
T, part-to-part
b. For every 14 candles, there are 4 red.
T, part-to-whole
c. For every 3 candles, there is one of each color.
F, incorrect part-to-whole. A correct part-to-whole might be: for every 14 candles there are 5 blue.
d. The ratio of red to blue is 5:4.
F, incorrect part-to-part. A correct part to part might be: the ratio of red to blue is 4:5
ACE 1-8

The sixth graders make a new box that holds 15 cupcakes. They want 10 green cupcakes for every 5 white cupcakes in the box. Write at least two ratios that are part to part and two ratios that are part to whole to describe this new box of cupcakes.

Possible answers include:

Part-to-Part:

For every 10 green cupcakes, there are 5 white cupcakes.

The ratio of white to green cupcakes is 5 to 10.

For every 2 green cupcakes, there is 1 white cupcake.

Part-to-Whole:

For every 15 cupcakes, there are 5 white cupcakes.

The ratio of green cupcakes to total cupcakes is 10 to 15.

For every 3 cupcakes, there is 1 white cupcake

The ratio of green cupcakes to total cupcakes is 2 to 3.

ACE 1-10
A fruit bar is 5 inches long. The bar will be split into two pieces. For each situation, find the lengths of the two pieces.
a. One piece is 3/10 of the whole bar.
3/10 of the whole bar equals 1.5 inches. Thus, the other piece is 3.5 inches.
b. One piece is 1 inch longer than the other.
If one piece is 1 inch longer than the other, this would mean one piece is 3 inches and one piece is 2 inches.

ACE 1-20

As part of the carnival, the school will hold a Factor Game marathon. It takes Nala and Tierra an average of 12 minutes to finish one game. About how many games will they finish if they play nonstop from 9:00a.m. to 2:30p.m.?
5 hours × 60 (minutes/ hour) = 300 minutes; 300 + 30 = 330 minutes. 330 ÷ 12 = 27.5. Therefore, they can play 27 games.
ACE 1-21

Multiple Choice Carlos read a book for language arts class. He finished the book on Friday. On Monday, je read 27 pages. On Tuesday, he read 31 pages. On Wednesday, he read 28 pages, On Thursday and Friday, he read the same number of pages each day. The book has 144 pages. How many pages did he read on Thursday?

A. 28

B. 29

C. 31

D. 58

Answer: B; Carlos read 27 + 31 + 28 = 86 pages the first part of the week. He had 144 - 86 = 58 pages left for Thursday and Friday. Since he read the same number of pages each day, 58 ÷ 2 = 29. Carlos read 29 pages on Thursday.
ACE 1-22
The variable n represents a whole number.
a. For what values of n will the sum n + 3 be less than 50?
For n + 3 < 50, the possible answers of n are 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, ..., 45, 46.
b. For what values of n will the product 3n be less than 50?
For 3n < 50, the possible answers of n are 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, ..., 15, 16.
ACE 1-23
a. Long ago, people decided to divide the day into units called hours. They chose 24 as the number of hours in one day. Why is 24 a more convenient choice than 23 or 25?

24 has many factors, so it can be divided into many equal parts. Since 23 is prime, it cannot be subdivided. The only proper factors of 25 are 1 and 5, so it can only be subdivided into 5 groups of 5.
b. In developing the ways of calculating time, astronomers divided an hour into 60 minutes. Why is 60 a better choice than 59 or 61?
Because 60 has many factors and 50 and 61 do not.
ACE 1-24
Ramona's aunt has saved $10,000 in $20 bills. She spends one $20 bill every day. How many days will it take her to run out of bills?
500 days, 10,000 divided by 20 = 500.

ACE 1-28

What number am I?

Clue 1. When you divide me by 5, the remainder is 4.

Clue 2. I have two digits. Both digits are odd.

Clue 3. The sum of my digits is 10.

The numbers that have two odd digits (Clue 2) and give a remainder of 4 when divided by 5 (Clue 1) are 19, 39, 59, 79, and 99. Of these numbers, 19 is the only one with digits that add to 10 (Clue 3). The number is 19.
ACE 1-29

The sum of the proper factors of a number may be greater than, less than, or equal to the number. Mathematicians use this idea to classify numbers as abundant, deficient, or perfect. Each whole number greater than 1 falls into one of these three categories.
a. Draw and label three circles as shown. The numbers 12, 15, and 6 have been placed in the appropriate circles.
Use your factor list to determine what each label means. Then, write each whole number from 2 to 30 in the correct circle.
b. Are the labels appropriate? Why or why not?

Abundant means "more than enough," which is appropriate since the sum of an abundant number's proper factors is more than the number. Deficient means "not enough," which is appropriate since the sum of a deficient number's proper factor is less than the number. Perfect means "exactly right," which is appropriate because the sum of a perfect number's proper factors is equal to the number.
c. In which circle does 36 belong?
Abundant.
d. In which circle does 55 belong?
Deficient.
ACE 1-30

Paloma works on many factor problems. She notices that her factor pair list often starts with pairs of numbers such as 1 × 100, 2 × 50, and 4 × 25. Her factor list ends with 25 × 4, 50 × 2, and 100 × 1. At some point, the list begins to repeat the factor pairs in reversed order.
a. Consider the factor pairs of 100. When do the factor pairs reverse order?
b. Consider the factor pairs of 81. When do the factor pairs reverse order?
c. For any square number, when do the factor pairs reverse order?
If students know of the square root, this is where the factors. reverse order. Another way to explain this is to find the factor pair that makes a square.
d. Think about a number that is not a square number. At what point will the factor pairs reverse order? Explain.

The factor pairs reverse order at the square root of the original number. Students may not have been exposed to square roots yet, and it is not necessary at this time. Geometrically, if you use the factor pairs to build rectangles, the rectangle that is closest to a square will be the last factor pair before the pairs reverse order.
e. Is there a point at which a prime number's factor pairs reverse order?
Yes, similar to ACE 30d. Because there are only two possible ways to write a prime number as a product of its factors, the turnaround occurs after the first pair.
ACE 1-31

Nuru is trying to determine when he can stop looking for more whole- number factors of a number. He has collected data about several numbers. For example, 30 has 1 × 30, 2 × 15, 3 × 10, and 5 × 6 as factor pairs. Then, he can stop looking because the factor pairs repeat. For 36, he can stop looking when he gets to 6 × 6. For 66, there are no new factor pairs after 6 × 11.

Copy and complete the following table. Is there any pattern that would help Nuru find the point where the factor pairs reverse order?

Students will most likely notice that they can stop looking for more factor pairs at the point the dimensions are most "square-like" because after that, the dimensions are in a reverse order. Students might notice that for square numbers, the last factor pair is the one that uses the square root, though they may not use that vocabulary word. Extending this idea to the non square numbers, they may say that looking for a square near the number being investigated helps; thus, 66 is close to 8 × 8, and 7 and 8 are not factors of 66, so there is no point in loking further than 6 × 11
ACE 1-32
For ACE 32a-c, find composite numbers that can be rewritten as the following:
a. the product of two prime numbers
Samples: 4 = 2 × 2, 9 = 3 × 3, ... 5 × 3 = 15, where 15 is composite and is the product of two primes.
b. the product of a prime number and another composite number
c. the product of two composite numbers
d. Oba thinks he can find examples of prime numbers that he can write as a product of two primes. Is he correct? Give some examples or explain why not.
No; prime numbers have only two factors, 1 and themselves. They couldn't be the product of to prime numbers, a prime number and another composite number, or two composite numbers.
